{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2hayden_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280604926/1949031801/0176.xml":{"full_text":"Two Investment Firms\nTo Fight Pepco Plan\nOn Bond Issue Sale\nTh\u00ab Potomac Electric Power\nCo.'s request for authority to issue\n$37,000,000 in unsecured bonds to\nfinance its new construction pro\ngram and refinance its funded\ndebt is expected to encounter\nstrong opposition Monday when\nthe Public Utilities Commission\nholds a public hearing on the\nplan.\nThe company has asked the\nPUC for permission to sell the\nbonds to three large insurance\ncompanies without bidding under\na waiver of a PUC rule requiring\ncompetitive bidding in marketing\nnew securities.\nThe commission announced to\nday that two out-of-town invest\nment brokerage companies have\nserved notice they will attend the\nhearing and oppose the waiver.\nThey are Halsey Stuart 61 Co.,\nChicago, and Otis Co., Cleve\nland.\nWould Be Sold to Insurance Firms.\nPepco's plan is to sell $13,000,\n000 worth of the debentures to\nthe Metropolitan Life Insurance\nCo., $12,000,000 to the Equitable\nLife Insurance Co. and $12,000,\n000 to the Prudential Life Insur\nance Co.\nThe company contends that\nprivate sale to the insurance firms\nwill realize more money.\nThe two brokerage firms, which\nhave appeared at hearings in\nmany cities to oppose private sale\nof utility securities to insurance\ncompanies, say competition brings\nlower financing costs.\nRules of both the PUC and the\nSecurities and Exchange Commis\nsion provide for not less than\nthree bidders unless the commis\nsion having jurisdiction believes\nthat money can be saved for the\nutility by a private sale.\nEconomy Factors Stressed.\nThe PUB will decide from the\ntestimony whether closed or com\npetitive bidding will be more ad\nvantageous for the company.\nR. Roy Dunn, treasurer for the\ncompany, said the anticipated\neconomy through a non-competi\ntive sale would result from two\nfactors.\nFirst he estimated the cost of\nseeking bids would be about $150,\n000, whereas the cost of arranging\nnon-competitive purchase of the\nsecurities by the insrance compa\nni es would be about $77,000.\nSecond, Mr. Dunn explained, if\na brokerage house were engaged\nto market the securities all the\ndebentures would have to be issued\nat once and interest would have\nto be paid on the entire $37,000,000\nfrom the day of issue. The insur\nance companies have offered \"take\ndown\" privileges whereby part of\nthe securities would be isuued at\nonce and the remainder some\nmonths later, saving part of the\nInterest.\nThe PUC recently permitted the\nWashington Gas Light Co. to sell\nsecurities on a similar non-com\npetitive basis, but this is the first\ntime Pepco has sought exemption\nasking for bids.\nReaction\n(Continued From First, Page. t j\nen Europe politically and econom\nically as well as militarily.\nIn Paris, French Foreign Min\nister Robert Schuman declared the\nalliance provides France with an\neffective shield against aggression.\n\"We are convinced,\u201d Mr. Schu\nman told newsmen, \u201cthat the pact\ncontains not only a moral but a\nJudicial engagement upon each\nsignatory to aid one another asl\nrapidly and as effectively as pos\nsible in the manner each deems\nbest, according to its means.\u201d\nThe minister asserted Article\nThree of the treaty requires each\nmember to augment its own de\nfensive potential, with the under\nstanding that economic recovery\nholds priority over armament.\nDenies Rearmament Plan.\nA reporter for a Communist\npaper asked the minister if it\nwould be \u201cexcessive\u201d to deduce\nthat the treaty implies a rearma\nment program for Fiance.\nMr. Schuman replied it would\nnot, and added: \u201cThe pact would\nnot mean anything if the mem\nber nations did not have any\narms.\u201d\n\u201cAt the present time,\u201d contin\nued Mr. Schuman, \"even if they\npooled all their equipment the\nnations of Western Europe would\nLOST.\nANTIQUE GOLD PIN, with pendant, con\ntainlng small family photograph, vie. park\ning lot opposite Lansburgh 8th st. ent.it\nsentimental value; reward. OR. 6028.:\n__\u20141\u00b0_ I\nBRIEFCASE, brown leather, zippered,\nvicinity Peace Cross; reward. CO. 3977 j\nor WA. 7440.\u201420\nCOCKER PUPPY, female, black, white1\nmarking on chest, children\u2019s pet. Reward.1\nREV. RAYMOND P. BLACK, Rockville\n*884._\u201419_\nCOCKER SPANIEL\u2014Won\u2019t you please\nbring our net back? Flaxen colored. 11\nmos. old; lost since Feb. 18th. American\nUniversity Park area. Liberal reward.\nWO 1128.\u20142o\nCOCKER SPANIEL PUPPY, tan: near\nWisconsin ave. and Ordway it. Reward.\nCall WO. 6120.\u201418_\nEARRING, p*arl. Reward. OR. 8267\n\u201419\nKEYS, on small ring; lost Wed. afternoon\non Ga. ave., near Sil. Bp. car house.\nReward. Call Bligo 7737._\u201419_\nKEYS, between 12th and Pa. ave. and\nI .\">th and H ats. n w. Reward. OV. 0549\nor RE. 4800._\u201420_\nMAN\u2019S BILLFOLD, brown, some cash and\nva'uable papers, in area of 14th and G\nn.w.. reward. J. J. ILGENFR1TZ, 608\nJeiferson st.. Alex.. Va. TE. 4297.\nOP1.RA GLASS' STICK, black with gold\ntr'- lost Sat. night March 12th in Con\nstitution Hall or vie.; sentimental va'lue.\nD 1843._\u2014IS\nPOCKETBOOK. black patent leather: on\nBarcroft bus Wed. noon; contains money.\n<h\u00bbckbook, etc.; reward. Call OL. 4400,\nEx' J011.\nF.T <G, lost in vicinity of 3rd and G sts.\nn.w.; man's ruby ring; reward. 609 3rd;\nat. n.w. ME. 4813. I\nWATCH, lady's wrist, white gold, black\nbar.d, between Conn, and M and Fed\neral Security Agency or in egb; reward.\nJ5X. 6300. Ext. 4278.\nWRIST WATCH. 14-k. gold; March 17.\nabout 8 a m., 1600 block Eye st. n.w.. or\nL bus rt.: reward. 'Mg, 8P6\u20193. \u201420\nWRIST WATCH, diamond and platinum.\nname and Penn, address on back. Liberal\nreward to finder. ISABEL P. FUSS, Dan\nvllle. Pa._ 19*\nWRIST WATCH, man\u2019s, Swiss Croton;\nThurs., March 10; O. W. student. Re\nward. WO. 7768.\u201419\nLOST\u2014Bridge work of 6 lower back teeth.\nCall KM. 3612._ _\u201418_\nREWARD FOR LOST DOG named \"Tobey.\u201d\nMale, tag 29436. Finder return 1620 10th\nat. n.w.. AD. 6339.\u20141\u00bb\n18-MM. SOUND FILM. \"Strange Ooda of\nIndia.\u201d Call OW. 7149. \u201420\nPOUND\nBLOND COCKER SPANIEL, tan and white,\nbetween 3 and 4 months old, vicinity Wis\nconsin ave. and Ordwy *t. EM. 3613.\nbOG, cocker-type, male, black, white spot\non throat; vlelnlty ol Minn, ave. and E.\nCapitol at. AK. S612.\n*EY RING, with 2 Ira. keys and 2 small\nkeys, found at 14th and G n.w. Call GE.\n6314\nMONET found' In Kanns Dept Store,\n-Thursday, March 17. Call WI. 7725. A\nCONTROVERSIAL PICTURE RELEASED\u2014The three dark smudges pictured here are Presi\ndent Truman (left) and two unidentified members of his party swimming at Key West, Fla.,\nlocation of the \u201cLittle White House.\u201d The air view was made Monday from a Navy blimp by an\nNBC Television Newsreel cameraman and was reviewed for \u201csecurity\u2019\u2019\u2019 reasons, by three members\nof the President\u2019s staff before distribution. The White House asked newsreel men to supply the\nAssociated Press, Acme News Photos and International News Photos with the pictures after\nphotographers for these organizations had destroyed their own negatives when told that beach\nand vacation \u201cLittle White House\u201d scenes never could be published.\n\u2014AP Photo from NBC Television Newsreel.\nTruman Refuses to Give Up Hope for Program\nfContinuedFrom First Page.\"*\nports quoting some Republicans as\nsaying that certain Democrats\nsftw eye-to-eve with them, Mr.\nTruman wanted to know what\nwas new about that. The same\ncondition always has prevailed, he\ncontinued.\nThe President said he knew\nnothing about a report that he\nmight call Congress back into a\nsummer special session to deal\nwith party measures which might\"\nfail in the regular session. With\nthis Congress still at work. Mr.\nTruman thought that sort of spec\nulation premature.\nToo Early for Speculation.\nWhen a reporter referred to a\nstatement by Senator Morse. Re\npublican. of Oregon, on a reported\nagreement by administration op\nponents on a skeletonized civil'\nrights bill. Mr. Truman comment\ned that the Oregon Senator is in\nWashington and he isn't.\nPhilosophizing. Mr. Truman said\nthat he simply makes recommen\ndations on what he thinks is good\nfor the country. This government\nis made up of three prongs, he\ncontinued\u2014Executive, Legislative\nand Judicial\u2014and neither should\ninterfere in the work of the other.\nMr. Truman said Winston\nChurchill, former British Prime\nMinister, will have lunch or din\nner with him next Thurslay.\nWill Speak at M. I. T.\nMr. Churchill speaks at Massa\nchusetts Institute of Technology\nMarch 31. and will be followed\nthere the next day by the Presi\ndent.\nMr. Truman said he would meet\nwith his legislative leaders Mon\nday as usual and also would see\nthe cabinet.\nThe President is ending his two\nweek vacation here tomorrow with\nregret, and returning to Wash\nington. He said he had been\nlooking for some excuse to stay\nanother week, but must be in the\nCapital tomorrow night to attend\nthe dinner of the White Housed\nNe\\vs Photographers\u2019 Association.\nThe news-photo censorship fu\nror which stirred Monday finally\nw?s /quieted yesterday when the\nnewsreels taken from a blimp\ncruising over the Presidential\nquarters were shown at the White\nHouse and approved with only one\ndeletion\u2014a panoramic view of the\n\u201cLittle White House.\u201d which was\ncut out for \u201csecurity\u201d reasons.\nCanada's Government\nStakes Life on 0. K.\nOf Atlantic Alliance\n\u2022y Associated Press\nOTTAWA, Ontario, Mar. 18.\n\u2014Prime Minister Louis St.\nLaurent today gave the Cana\ndian House of Commons the\ndraft text of the North At\nlantic treaty and staked the\ngovernment's life on its gen\neral acceptance by Parliament.\nThe Prime Minister gave\nnotice of a resolution approv\ning its principles and asking\nthe House to recognize the\nproposed treaty as \"of vital\nimportance for the protection\nof Canada, the preservation of\npeace and the development of\npolitical, social and economic\nco-operation among North\nAmerican democracies.\u201d\nnot have enough strength to\nstand up against possible threats.\u201d\nMr. Schuman emphasized that\nthe treaty was purely defensive\nand would be invoked only in case\nof an organized aggression by\nsome other government against a\nsignatory state.\nA copy of the treaty was handed\nto United Nations Secretary Gen\neral Trygve Lie at Lake Success\nlast night by the American dele\ngation.\nIn The Hague, Dutch Foreign\nMinister D. U. Stikker declared\nthe new alliance is \"of the great\nest importance to the world,\u201d be\ncause for the first time the United\nStates and Canada have been\nwilling to engage themselves in\nsuch a grouping.\nHe told a news conference the\nDutch government considers the\ntreaty \u2018\u2018generally completely sat\nisfactory\u201d and added:\n\u201cWe believe that the forces de\nveloped by all participant coun\ntires, including 250,000,000 people,\nwill be big enough to take away\nany idea of attacking.\u201d\nThere was opposition in Britain,\ntoo. W. N. Warbey, a Laborite\nmember of Parliament, said the\nnew alliance could only sen/e to\nsplit the world in two \u201cand lead\nthe world into war.\u201d Phil Piratin,\na Communist member of the\nhouse, recalled the words of Ne\nville Chamberlain 10 years ago\nwhen he returned from Munich to\ndeclare he had brought \u201cpeace in\nour time.\u201d\n\u201cI believe.\u201d said Piratin, \u201cthat\nthis historic occasion will go down\nin history to be as damned as that\none was.\u201d\nGloucester to Vote\nOn Negro School Issue\nBy th\u00ab Associated Frost\nGLOUCESTER, Va., Mar. 18.\u2014\nGloucester County residents will\nvote March 31 whether to sup\nport a $300,000 bond issue to\nfinance Negro school improve\nments in the county.\nThe date was announced yes\nterday after the signing of a court\norder by Circuit Court Judge J.\nDouglas Mitchell.\nThe School Board has tempo\nrarily put aside plans for the con\nstruction of a new white high\nschool. The board now will seek\nonly enough money to provide\nequal facilities for Negro pupils as\nthe Federal Court directed in the\naction several months ago.\nThe action on the bond issue is\nthe School Board\u2019s answer to a\ncontempt citation by Federal\nJudge Sterling Hutcheson in Jan\nuary, in which Gloucester school\nofficials were accused of disregard\ning a court order to equalise\nNegro and white facilities. Offi\ncials must face the court next\nmonth for imposition of penaltfts.\nTerms of Alliance Made Public\n(Continued From First Page.>\nin history linking the two con\ntinents.\nIn addition to the key provisions\nconcerning a possible armed at\ntack. major provisions of the\ntreaty would pledge the participat\ning nations to:\n1. Separate and joint action\nnow to \"maintain and develop\ntheir individual and collective ca\npacity to resist armed attack\u201d by\nmeans of \"continuous and effec\ntive self-help and mutual aid.\u201d\n2. \"Establish immediatelv a de\nfense committee\u201d to recommend\npractical measures for carrying\nout these pledges.\nEight nations\u2014the United\nStates, Canada, Great Britain.\nFrance, Belgium, the Netherlands,;\nLuxembourg and Norway\u2014have\nagreed to sign the treaty here dur\ning the first week of April, prob\nably on April 4. They have in\nvited Italy, Denmark, Iceland and\nPortugal to join them, and those\ncountries are expected to do so.\nBefore it becomes effective, how\never. the treaty would have to be\nratified by the United States Sen\nate and by a majority of the other\nnations signing it, including Can\nada and the five Western Euro\npean Union countries. It would\nremain in force for at least 20\nyears, with provision for review\nafter 10 years in the light of con\nditions then if any member re\nquests it.\nThe area to be defended under\nthe alliance is limited to North\nAmerica, Europe, Algeria in North\nAfrica and the Atlantic Ocean\nnorth of the Tropic of Cancer,\nwhich is 23 degrees, 27 minutes\nnorth latitude. In this area\nan attack on any of the\nalliance members, their occupation i\nforces in Europe, their Atlantic:\nisland possessions or their ships\nor airplanes would be regarded as\nan attack on all.\nConsultation Provided for.\nUnder a general provision, the\ntreaty calls for joint consults-;\ntion if any member believes its\n\u201cterritorial Integrity, political in-j\ndependence or security\u2019\u2019 is threat\nened.\nMr. Acheson emphasized that\nthis consultation provision is much\nbroader in scope than the article\nproviding for action to meet an\narmed attack. He said any de\nvelopments anywhere in the world\nwhich a member of the alliance\nconsidered affected its security\nwould require consultation.\nThe treaty neither obligates the\nmembers to take any action, nor\nlimits their possible action, con\ncerning any security threats ex\ncept an armed attack in the speci\nfied North Atlantic area, Mr. Ache\nson pointed out.\nDefinition Is Impossible.\nHe told questioners it was im\npossible to define what would be\n{considered an \u201carmed attack\u2019\u2019 in\njail circumstances. He said he be\nlieved an attack on one of the\nAmerican planes flying the airlift\nto Berlin over the Soviet Bone\nwould be so considered.\nIt might apply also, he said, to\nrevolutionary activity in one of\nthe nations a party to the treaty\nif that .activity was assisted from\nthe outside\u2014such as the Com\nmunist warfare against the Greek\ngovernment. But purely internal\nrevolutionary activity would not\nbe an \u201carmed attack,\u201d although it\nmight require consultation, he\nadded.\nMr. Acheson said there may be\nsome areas where United States\nobligations would overlap in the\nNorth Atlantic treaty and in the\ninter-American defense 4 pact..\nThere is nothing in the Atlantic\ntreaty, however, he said, to in\ncrease obligations of the Latin\nAmerican nations* which earlier\njoined this country in the hem\nisphere pact.\nHe evaded any specific answer\nabout whether Spain might be fa\nvored as a member of the North\nAtlantic alliance. The treaty pro\nvides that original signers may by\nunanimous agreement invite any\nOther European nation \"in a posi\ntion to further\u201d its principles and\ncontribute to tty* /security of the\narea to accede to the pact. Treaty.\nprinciples include \"democracy, in\ndividual liberty and the rule of\nlaw.\u201d He said he supposed there\ncould be much debate about Spain\nin relation to such principles.\nMr. Acheson emphasized at the\noutset of his news conference that!\nthe treaty is purely defensive in\ncharacter, pointing out that the\nvery first article reaffirms determi\nnation of the participating nations\nto settle any international disputes\nin which they may be involved by\npeaceful means.\nAim to Strengthen U. N.\nDrafters of the treaty took great\npains to make clear it is designed!\nto strengthen rather than to;\nweaken the United Nations. The\nUnited Nations or its Security\nCouncil are mentioned specifically\nnine times in the 14 articles of the\nproposed pact.\nAlliance members will be\npledged to refrain from using;\nforce or the threat of force \u201cin\nany manner inconsistent with the\npurposes of the United Nations.\u201d\nTo back up the \"self-help and\nmutual aid\u201d concept of the treaty,\nthe State Department is preparing\nlegislation under which Congress\nwill be asked to authorize Pres\nident Truman to provide American\nmilitary equipment to help build\nup the armed forces of the Eu\nropean alliance members.\nThis program is expected to cost\nmore than $1,000,000,000 for the;\nfirst year, although no official!\nestimate has been made yet. The|\nState Department explained that\nthe aim for the first year will be!\nto equip fully existing military\nforces of the European members,\nwith building up of additional\nforces to be considered later.\nEastern Star Tea Tomorrow\nThe annual benefit silver tea of\nthe Home Board, of Esther Chap\nter, No. 5, Order of the Eastern\nStar, will be held from 3 to 6\np.m. tomorrow at the home of\nMrs. J. Harry Phillips, 1336 In\ngraham street N.W.\nShamrock Sellers\nHeld in Los Angeles\nGet Free Defense\n\u2022y th\u00bb AnoclaUd Pr\u00abt\nLOS ANGELES. Mar. 18\nFour men were arrested here\nfor selling Shamrocks on St.\nPatrick\u2019s Day.\nThe arresting officers were\nnot Clancy or Murphy but\nR. R. Fusiler and J. L. La\nMonica. The men were charged\nwith violation of a city or\ndinance in selling on a side\nwalk without a license.\nAttorney Patrick Joseph\nCooney, candidate for State\nattorney general, Immediately\ncalled it an \"outrage\u201d and said\nhe would defend them free.\n\"The sacredness and ob\nservance of St. Patrick\u2019s Day\nand the dignity of the Irish\nmust be upheld at all costs.\nImagine arresting men for\nselling Shamrocks.\u201d he roared.\nNone of the men arrested\nhas an Irish name.\n2 Ex-Policemen Get\nSforebreaking Parole\nTwo former Arlington police\nmen have been placed on proba\ntion for five years for storebreak\ning while on duty last November.\nCircuit Court Judge Walter T.\nMcCarthy of Arlington imposed\nthe penalties today on Louie L.\nLipptrap, 24, and Charles H.\nJames, 28, both of whom are mar\nried and have children.\nIn placing the men on proba\ntion, Judge McCarthy suspended\nfive-year jail sentences imposed\non each man February 21. They\nhave been in jail since that time.\nJudge McCarthy suspended the\nbalance of the term subject to<\nconditions to be laid down by the\nprobation officer.'\nThe judge told the men they\nwould find it difficult to follow\nthe conditions of their parole. He\nsai dthey had caused a great deal\nof trouble to their families, the\nPolice Department and the public.\nLipptrap and James pleaded\nguilty January 28 to a charge of\nbreaking into a grocery at 4717\nLee highway November 16. They\nwere arrested after being found\nstanding outside the door to the\ngrocery about 4 a.m.\nRomanian Nationalization;\nOf U. S. Property Protested\nBy th* Associated Press\nThe United States has protested\nagainst Romania's plan to na\ntionalize properties belonging to\nAmerican citizens.\nThe State Department said yes- j\nterday the American Legation in\nBucharest has sent a note to the\nRomanian Foreign Office saying\nthe plan fails to provide \"prompt,\nadequate or effective compensa\ntion.\u201d\nIn view of this, the State De\npartment said it has no inten\ntion of advising American citizens\nto apply for compensation as re\nquested by the Romanian gov\nernment.\nFurthermore, the State Depart\nment said it will reserve all rights\non behalf of American citizens!\nwhose property is being seized.\nThe United States, it said, will;\nhold the Romanian government\nresponsible \"for the return of\nproperties or for prompt payment:\nof adequate and effective compen\nsation therefor.\u201d\nA survey made in 1943 estimated\nthe value of American properties\nin Romania at $66.lt>0.000, of\nwhich $28,000,000 was in petro\nleum refineries and connected in\ndustries. The properties were\nowned by 137 corporations and\nAmerican citizens.\nRussian Union Paper Hits\nNorwegian Labor Party\nly th\u00ab A\u00bb$ociot*d Pr*s*\nMOSCOW, Mar. 18 \u2014The Soviet\ntrade union newspaper Trud to\nday blasted what it termed the\n\u201cn#w aggressive policy\u201d of Nor\nway\u2019s Labor Party and called for\na Norwegian-Russian nonaggres\nsion pact to reduce \u201ctension in\nthe North.\u201d\nTrud said the policies of the\nLabor Party is \u201cin contradiction\nwith th$ ancient friendly rela\ntions between the U. S. S. R. and\nNorway.\u201d\nThe editorial discussed at length\nthe present situation in Norway\nin relation to the North Atlantic j\nalliance.\nIt claimed the Norwegian peo\nple wanted a nonaggression pact\nwith Russia and \u201cthis is in fact\nwhy the leaders of foreign policy\nhurried so to declare Norway read\niness to Join the aggressive North\nAtlantic pact.\u201d\nNorway has turned down a Rus\nsian offer of a nonaggression pact\non the grounds that membership\nof' both countries in the United\nNations made such a treaty un\nnecessary.\nPayne School Students\nGive $25 to Symphony\nPupils of the Payne Elementary\nSchool, Fifteenth and C streets\nN.E., today presented to Conductor\nHoward Mitchell of the National\nSymphony Orchestra a donation\nof $25 for the symphony's sus\ntaining fund drive.\nThe first such donation from a\ncolored elementary school in the\norchestra's history, according to.\nMr. Mitchell, the money was\nraised among the children them\nselves at a special benefit movie\nshow at the school.\nFourth-grader Richard Gaither.\n9. 25 Seventeenth street S.E., son\nof a disabled Army veteran, made\nthe presentation. Miss Edith\nLyons, director of Division 13 of\nthe public schools, also was\npresent.\n51 Downtown Shops Begin\nThursday Night Hours\nFifty-one downtown shops in\naugurated the return of Thurs\nday night shopping last night.\nAn observer of the Merchants\nManufacturers Association said\nreports from some of the partici\npating shops indicated the volume\nof business was at least satisfac\ntory and in some cases very brisk.\nCrowds were spotty along the\nF and G street shopping district,\nbut it was anticipated the number\nof shoppers would increase as\nmore people learned of the new\nThursday closing hour, which is\n8:30 o\u2019clock in most cases.\nThe stores Include most of the\nwomen\u2019s apparel shops in the\ndowntown area, furniture, linen\nand other stores, but not the large\ndepartment stores or five anc5\n10-eent stores.\nWHY NOT?\nIt costs bo more\nto park at the\nCapital Garage\nNew York Avenue\nbetween 13th end 14th\nAtlantic Alliance More Direct\nThan Rio Pact in Pledae of Aid\nBy the Associated Pros*\nThe proposed North Atlantic\ntreaty makes a simpler, more di\nrect promise of Allied intention to\nresist any attack than the Rio\ndefense pact which the United\nStates made with the American\nnations in 1947.\nThe Atlantic treaty defense\nclause specifically mentions the\npossibility of \u201cthe use of armed\nforce\" against an aggressor,\nwhereas the inter American\ntreaty reserves the listing of this\npossibility for another and less\nspotlighted article.\nThe underlying reason for this\ndifference is that negotiators of\nthe Atlantic agreement felt that\nthe people of Western Europe\nmust be given the strongest possi\nble assurance, short of an auto\nmatic commitment to go to war,\nthat the power of the United\nStates is firmly allied with them\nin any trouble with the Soviet\nUnion.\nBoth the Inter-American treaty\nand the North-Atlantic pact de\nclare the principle that an at\ntack on any one of the allies shall\nbe considered an attack on all.\nThe Inter-American pact then\ngoes on to say that if an attack\noccurs and the victim asks help,\neach of the other members of\nthe alliance \u201cmay determine the\nI immediate measures which it\nmay individually take\u201d in line\nwith its commitment to assist in\nmeeting the attack.\nThe North Atlantic treaty, after\ndeclaring the one-for-all and all\nfor-one position, says the Allies\nagree that if an attack occurs\n\u201ceach of then will assist the\nparty or parties so attacked by\ntaking forthwith such action\nas, it deems necessary, including\nthe use of armed force, to restore\nand maintain the security of the\nNorth Atlantic area.\u201d\nThe Inter-American agreement,\nsigned at Rio de Janeiro Septem\nber 2, 1947, runs for 26 articles\nand more than 2,000 words. Its\nstyle is characterized by high\nflown phraseology and familiar\ndiplomatic formalisms.\nTo cover the same set of ideas,\nthe North Atlantic treaty runs\napproximately 1,000 words and is\ndivided into 14 articles. Its word\ning is, for the most part, direct\nand simple.\nFive Italian Labor* Leaders\nLeave for America Tuesday\nfty th\u00ab Anociotvd Pr\u00abt\nROME, Mar. 18.\u2014Five Italian\nlabor leaders will leave by ship\nfrom Genoa next Tuesday for a\n10-week American good-will tour\narranged by the American Fed\neration of Labor.\nThe group will be joined in\nGenoa by five French labor leaders\nwho also will be guests of the AFL,\nit was announced here today.\nThe tutor will take them from\nNew York to Washington, Pitts\nburgh, Detroit, St. Louis, Denver\nand to Tennessee Valley Author\nity projects.\nThe Italian labor leaders, all\nanti-Communists, are Renato\nCappugi, an executive director of\nthe autonomous Italian Railway\nUnion and a member of the anti\ncommunist Free Labor Confed\neration; Vasco Cesari, national\nsecretary of the Electrical Work\ners\u2019 Union and a Labor Socialist\nmember; Giovanni Pasqualino,\nRepublican Party-labor official;\nAlessandro Cappelletti. organizing\ndirector of the Farm Workers\u2019\nUnion, and Antonia Malagutti.\norganizer for the Women\u2019s Textile\nWorkers. _\nNourse Optimistic\nOn Business Outlook\nCHICAGO, Mar. 18\u2014Unless\nbusinessmen or consumers get\npanicky, the Nation this year\nshould be only slightly less proper\nous\u2014and possibly better off\u2014than\nin 1948, Edwin G. Nourse, chair\nman of the President\u2019s council of\nEconomic Advisers, said today.\nAs a result of \"the disinflation\nof 1949, we may take off some fat,\nbut we shall not die and need not\nreally suffer,\" he told the Ex\necutive's Clubs of Chicago.\n\u201cIt is noe the voice of Pollyanna\nbut of business statistics that says\nthat underlying conditions are\nsound and basically favorable,\"\nhe declares.\n\u201c1949 shoud show a sustained\nvolume of consumer spending and\nhence employment only very\nmoderately beyow last year, pro\nduction even higher, and prices\nadpusted to a better structure\nand a level somewhat but not\nseriously below the peaks of 1948.\u201d\nProfits should be \u201cas well as\nor better maintained over the\nlong pull\u201d when industry is work\ning at 90 per cent of capacity, Mr.\nNourse said, as under the \u201crecent\nstrained conditions\u201d when mills\nand mines were forced to 100 per\ncent capacity.\nBurmese Planes Bomb\nRebel-Held Mandalay\nBy the Associated Press\nRANGOON, Burma, Mar. 18\nBurmese planes bombed Mandalay\nfor the first time last night, strik\ning at Karen positions in the\nsacred city, it was announced to\nday.\nBurmese newspapers said the\nrebels took shelter in the city's\nBuddhist temples and directed\nantiaircraft fire at the attackers.\nMandalay is now held by Karen\nand Communist forces.\nThe aRngoon press said rebel\nforces burned two rice mills yes\nterday at Natmaw, northwest of\nRangoon, destroying 3.000 tons of\ngovernment-owned rice.\nPlane With 15 Aboard\nCrashes in New Zealand\nBy the Associated Press\nAUCKLAND, New Zealand, Mar.\n18.\u2014A passenger plane with 15\naboard was wrecked yesterday in,\na hilly area 30 miles north of\nWellington.\nAir search headquarters said it\nhad received reports the plane was\ncompletely broken up and burn\ning. There was no immediate\nword about the 13 passengers and\ncrew of two.\n26x69_\u201817*\n28x6/9.. *17\"\n10xfr9..\u201818\u201c\n30x71.. \u201818\".\nmain ornci IETKSM, Ml. \u00bbh9ni Wl. N22 I\nMANCII^jj^MIAll^Mi^ANOMIMIN^ajI^\nIsraeli-Lebanon Armistice\nPath Is Reported Clear\nBy the Associated Press\nTEL AVIV,** Israel, Mar. 18\nAn Israeli Foreign Office spokes\nman said today the main ob\nstacles for signing an Israel\nis banon armistice agreement now\nhave been removed.\n\"It can be expected that an\nagreement will be signed at the\nbeginning of next week,\u201d he\nadded.\nThe armistice talks opened at\nthe border town o\"f Ras en Naqura\non March 1. There had been re\nports that one of the sticking\npoints would concern the presence\nof Syrian troops on Palestine soil.\nThe Israel-Trans-Jordan armis\ntice talks now going on at Rhodes\nwere reported snagged. Mean\nwhile, on the presence of British\ntroops at Aqaba. Aqaba is Trans\nJordan\u2019s Red Sea port and British j\ntroops are there at Trans-Jordan\u2019s\nrequest, under a treaty tie. Aqaba\nis only two or three miles from\nIsraeli-claimed territory.\nLoaded U. S. Airliff.Plane\nCrashes at Berlin; 3 Escape\nBy th\u00ab Associated Press\nBERLIN, Mar. 18.\u2014A fully-'\nloaded American airlift cargoj\nplane crashed at Tempelhof Air\nfield early today and all three\ncrewmen escaped unhurt.\nThe plane, a four-engined C-54,\ntipped over in a ditch on the snow\ncovered field. Berlin had experi\nenced its heaviest snowfall of the\nwinter during the night. But\nground crews had most of it re\nmoved from the big field by the\ntime of the crash.\nThe pilot, co-pilot and engineer\nwere shaken up but otherwise\nescaped injury, the Air Force said.\nOfficials said later the plane\novershot the runway. It was\nloaded with 10 tons of coal and\nother materials for German in\ndustry. v\n11 on Plane Reported\nLost in Bay of Bengal\nBy the Associated Press\nRANGOON, Burma, Mar. 18.\u2014\nNine passengers and the two-man\ncrew are believed to have died\nwhen a government-owned pas\nsenger plane plunged into the Bay\nof Bengal Monday on a short\nflight from Moulmein to Rangoon, j\nThe plane's British pilot was\nCapt. H. P. SpaTrow. Others\naboard were Burmese, Indian and\nChinese nationals.\nBelated reports from villagers\nwho said they saw the plane dive\ninto the bay gave the first clue to\nfate of the missing craft.\nSnowstorm Disrupts\nt\nNew York Travel\nj By th\u00ab Associated Press\nNEW YORK, Mar. 18. \u2014Snow\ndriven by a northeast wind today\ndisrupted water and air traffic In\nMetropolitan New York and small\ncraft warnings wexe hoisted for\nmost of the Atlantic coast.\nThe American freighter Chris\ntian Bergh went aground on the\nbeach at Seabright, N. J.. in the\nswirling snowstorm. The 7,176\nton vessel inbound from Greece,\nwas being pounded by the surf less\nthan two miles south of Fort Han\ncock. The Coast Guard did not\nbelieve the vessel was in danger of\nbreaking up.\nForty-two domestic passenger\nflights at La Guardia Field were\ncanceled, and half a dozen trans\nAtlantic flights were delayed.\nThe Weather Bureau predicted\nthe snow would become mixed\nwith rain as the day progressed.\nThe Weather Bureau here had\nordered small craft warnings up at\n4 a.m. from Block, Island to the\nVirginia Capes. Later the Weather\nBureau at Miami ordered similar\nwarnings extended from both\ncoasts of Florida to Cape Hatteras,\nN. C.\nCardinal Sends $65 Checks\nTo Families of Strikers\nly th* Associated Press\nNEW YORK, Mar. 18.\u2014Gift\nchecks for $65 have been mailed\nby Francis Cardinal Spellman to\neach of the families of 275 worker*\nwho struck recently at two Cath\nolic cemeteries.\nCardinal Spellman for a week\nled young priests and seminarian*\nin digging graves at Calvary\nCemetery in Queens, where moro\nthgn 1.000 bodies accumulated\nduring the two-month strike. Th#\nworkers also struck at Gate of\nHeaven Cemetery, Hawthorne,\nN. Y.\nMsgr. George E. Ehardt, man\naging director of the New York\nArchdiocesan cemeteries, an\nnounced the mailing of the check*\ntoday. He stressed that they wer#\n\u201cgifts to the families,\u201d and said\nthey were accompanied by letter*\nin which the Cardinal said that;\nundoubtedly the period of no work\n\"has caused you and your family\nmany hardships.\"\nThe $65 is slightly more than\none week's pay of *64.35 provided\nin the agreement which ended th*\nstrike March 11.\nHundreds of housewives phoned\nDr. Edith Summerskill, secretary\nof Britain's Food Ministry, to pro\ntest after she said it was not pos\nsible to distinguish the taste of\nmargarine from butter.\n20\nPIECE\nOxford Dlnnorworo Sot\nONLY $1.39\nWith every tack of Kaaco Chick Starter and\nGrowing Math, you get a valuable coupon.\nSave only IS of theta coupon., plua *1.3t\nand get a complete 20-piece eat of lovely\nOxford di